#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:2
msgid "Changing standard (Python) test discovery"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:5
msgid "Ignore paths during test collection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:7
msgid ""
"You can easily ignore certain test directories and modules during collection "
"by passing the :option:`--ignore=path` option on the cli. ``pytest`` allows "
"multiple ``--ignore`` options. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:11
msgid ""
"tests/\n"
"|-- example\n"
"|   |-- test_example_01.py\n"
"|   |-- test_example_02.py\n"
"|   '-- test_example_03.py\n"
"|-- foobar\n"
"|   |-- test_foobar_01.py\n"
"|   |-- test_foobar_02.py\n"
"|   '-- test_foobar_03.py\n"
"'-- hello\n"
"    '-- world\n"
"        |-- test_world_01.py\n"
"        |-- test_world_02.py\n"
"        '-- test_world_03.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:28
msgid ""
"Now if you invoke ``pytest`` with ``--ignore=tests/foobar/test_foobar_03.py "
"--ignore=tests/hello/``, you will see that ``pytest`` only collects test-"
"modules, which do not match the patterns specified:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:31
msgid ""
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 5 items\n"
"\n"
"tests/example/test_example_01.py .                                   [ 20%]\n"
"tests/example/test_example_02.py .                                   [ 40%]\n"
"tests/example/test_example_03.py .                                   [ 60%]\n"
"tests/foobar/test_foobar_01.py .                                     [ 80%]\n"
"tests/foobar/test_foobar_02.py .                                     [100%]\n"
"\n"
"========================= 5 passed in 0.02 seconds ========================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:46
msgid ""
"The :option:`--ignore-glob` option allows to ignore test file paths based on "
"Unix shell-style wildcards. If you want to exclude test-modules that end "
"with ``_01.py``, execute ``pytest`` with :option:`--ignore-glob='*_01.py'`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:50
msgid "Deselect tests during test collection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:52
msgid ""
"Tests can individually be deselected during collection by passing the :"
"option:`--deselect=item` option. For example, say ``tests/foobar/"
"test_foobar_01.py`` contains ``test_a`` and ``test_b``. You can run all of "
"the tests within ``tests/`` *except* for ``tests/foobar/test_foobar_01.py::"
"test_a`` by invoking ``pytest`` with ``--deselect=tests/foobar/"
"test_foobar_01.py::test_a``. ``pytest`` allows multiple ``--deselect`` "
"options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:61
msgid "Keeping duplicate paths specified from command line"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:63
msgid ""
"Default behavior of ``pytest`` is to ignore duplicate paths specified from "
"the command line. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:66
msgid ""
"pytest path_a path_a\n"
"\n"
"...\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:74
msgid "Just collect tests once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:76
msgid ""
"To collect duplicate tests, use the :option:`--keep-duplicates` option on "
"the cli. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:79
msgid ""
"pytest --keep-duplicates path_a path_a\n"
"\n"
"...\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:89
msgid "Changing directory recursion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:91
msgid ""
"You can set the :confval:`norecursedirs` option in a configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:93
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.toml\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"norecursedirs = [\".svn\", \"_build\", \"tmp*\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:99
msgid ""
"This would tell ``pytest`` to not recurse into typical subversion or sphinx-"
"build directories or into any ``tmp`` prefixed directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:104
msgid "Changing naming conventions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:106
msgid ""
"You can configure different naming conventions by setting the :confval:"
"`python_files`, :confval:`python_classes` and :confval:`python_functions` in "
"your :ref:`configuration file <config file formats>`. Here is an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:111
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.toml\n"
"# Example 1: have pytest look for \"check\" instead of \"test\"\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"python_files = [\"check_*.py\"]\n"
"python_classes = [\"Check\"]\n"
"python_functions = [\"*_check\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:120
msgid ""
"This would make ``pytest`` look for tests in files that match the ``check_* ."
"py`` glob-pattern, ``Check`` prefixes in classes, and functions and methods "
"that match ``*_check``. For example, if we have:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:124
msgid ""
"# content of check_myapp.py\n"
"class CheckMyApp:\n"
"    def simple_check(self):\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    def complex_check(self):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:134
msgid "The test collection would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:136
msgid ""
"$ pytest --collect-only\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"configfile: pytest.toml\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"\n"
"<Dir pythoncollection.rst-214>\n"
"  <Module check_myapp.py>\n"
"    <Class CheckMyApp>\n"
"      <Function simple_check>\n"
"      <Function complex_check>\n"
"\n"
"======================== 2 tests collected in 0.12s ========================"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:153
msgid ""
"You can check for multiple glob patterns by adding a space between the "
"patterns:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:155
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.toml\n"
"# Example 2: have pytest look for files with \"test\" and \"example\"\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"python_files = [\"test_*.py\", \"example_*.py\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:164
msgid ""
"the ``python_functions`` and ``python_classes`` options have no effect for "
"``unittest.TestCase`` test discovery because pytest delegates discovery of "
"test case methods to unittest code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:169
msgid "Interpreting cmdline arguments as Python packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:171
msgid ""
"You can use the :option:`--pyargs` option to make ``pytest`` try "
"interpreting arguments as python package names, deriving their file system "
"path and then running the test. For example if you have unittest2 installed "
"you can type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:176
msgid "pytest --pyargs unittest2.test.test_skipping -q"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:180
msgid ""
"which would run the respective test module.  Like with other options, "
"through a configuration file and the :confval:`addopts` option you can make "
"this change more permanently:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:184
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.toml\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = [\"--pyargs\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:190
msgid ""
"Now a simple invocation of ``pytest NAME`` will check if NAME exists as an "
"importable package/module and otherwise treat it as a filesystem path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:195
msgid "Finding out what is collected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:197
msgid ""
"You can always peek at the collection tree without running tests like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:199
msgid ""
". $ pytest --collect-only pythoncollection.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"configfile: pytest.toml\n"
"collected 3 items\n"
"\n"
"<Dir pythoncollection.rst-214>\n"
"  <Dir CWD>\n"
"    <Module pythoncollection.py>\n"
"      <Function test_function>\n"
"      <Class TestClass>\n"
"        <Function test_method>\n"
"        <Function test_anothermethod>\n"
"\n"
"======================== 3 tests collected in 0.12s ========================"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:221
msgid "Customizing test collection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:225
msgid ""
"You can easily instruct ``pytest`` to discover tests from every Python file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:227
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.toml\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"python_files = [\"*.py\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:233
msgid ""
"However, many projects will have a ``setup.py`` which they don't want to be "
"imported. Moreover, there may be files only importable by a specific python "
"version. For such cases you can dynamically define files to be ignored by "
"listing them in a ``conftest.py`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:238
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import sys\n"
"\n"
"collect_ignore = [\"setup.py\"]\n"
"if sys.version_info[0] > 2:\n"
"    collect_ignore.append(\"pkg/module_py2.py\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:247
msgid "and then if you have a module file like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:249
msgid ""
"# content of pkg/module_py2.py\n"
"def test_only_on_python2():\n"
"    try:\n"
"        assert 0\n"
"    except Exception, e:\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:258
msgid "and a ``setup.py`` dummy file like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:260
msgid ""
"# content of setup.py\n"
"0 / 0  # will raise exception if imported"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:265
msgid ""
"If you run with a Python 2 interpreter then you will find the one test and "
"will leave out the ``setup.py`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:268
msgid ""
"#$ pytest --collect-only\n"
"====== test session starts ======\n"
"platform linux2 -- Python 2.7.10, pytest-2.9.1, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile: pytest.ini\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"<Module 'pkg/module_py2.py'>\n"
"  <Function 'test_only_on_python2'>\n"
"\n"
"====== 1 tests found in 0.04 seconds ======"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:280
msgid ""
"If you run with a Python 3 interpreter both the one test and the ``setup."
"py`` file will be left out:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:283
msgid ""
"$ pytest --collect-only\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"configfile: pytest.toml\n"
"collected 0 items\n"
"\n"
"======================= no tests collected in 0.12s ========================"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:294
msgid ""
"It's also possible to ignore files based on Unix shell-style wildcards by "
"adding patterns to :globalvar:`collect_ignore_glob`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:297
msgid ""
"The following example ``conftest.py`` ignores the file ``setup.py`` and in "
"addition all files that end with ``*_py2.py`` when executed with a Python 3 "
"interpreter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:301
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import sys\n"
"\n"
"collect_ignore = [\"setup.py\"]\n"
"if sys.version_info[0] > 2:\n"
"    collect_ignore_glob = [\"*_py2.py\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:310
msgid ""
"Since Pytest 2.6, users can prevent pytest from discovering classes that "
"start with ``Test`` by setting a boolean ``__test__`` attribute to ``False``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:313
msgid ""
"# Will not be discovered as a test\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    __test__ = False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:321
msgid ""
"If you are working with abstract test classes and want to avoid manually "
"setting the ``__test__`` attribute for subclasses, you can use a mixin class "
"to handle this automatically. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:325
msgid ""
"# Mixin to handle abstract test classes\n"
"class NotATest:\n"
"    def __init_subclass__(cls):\n"
"        cls.__test__ = NotATest not in cls.__bases__\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"# Abstract test class\n"
"class AbstractTest(NotATest):\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"# Subclass that will be collected as a test\n"
"class RealTest(AbstractTest):\n"
"    def test_example(self):\n"
"        assert 1 + 1 == 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/pythoncollection.rst:343
msgid ""
"This approach ensures that subclasses of abstract test classes are "
"automatically collected without needing to explicitly set the ``__test__`` "
"attribute."
msgstr ""
